<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/3EAE04CA-9D62-4483-B9C4-F91AD9F4C5A9"><gtr:id>3EAE04CA-9D62-4483-B9C4-F91AD9F4C5A9</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Oxford</gtr:name><gtr:department>Politics and International Relations</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University Chest</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Wellington Square</gtr:line2><gtr:line4>Oxford</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>OX1 2JD</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>South East</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/3EAE04CA-9D62-4483-B9C4-F91AD9F4C5A9"><gtr:id>3EAE04CA-9D62-4483-B9C4-F91AD9F4C5A9</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Oxford</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University Chest</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Wellington Square</gtr:line2><gtr:line4>Oxford</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>OX1 2JD</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>South East</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/41649415-EA17-4023-B519-89D8D8A71BDE"><gtr:id>41649415-EA17-4023-B519-89D8D8A71BDE</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Varun</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Uberoi</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FH009825%2F1"><gtr:id>9BB56790-7AC9-4504-8327-75274A200FEC</gtr:id><gtr:title>The Theory And Practice Of Fostering Unity Amongst The Culturally Diverse Citizens Of Modern Polities</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/H009825/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This research project focuses on the theory and practice of fostering unity amongst the culturally diverse citizens of modern polities. In doing so, it addresses fundamental questions that have, until now, been neglected. These questions include: &lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>what precisely is unity amongst the citizens of a polity,&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>how does such unity differ from similar ideas like belonging and loyalty,&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>why is unity so difficult to foster amongst those who are culturally diverse &lt;/li>

 &lt;li>what have governments done to address this difficulty?&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>

&lt;p>Such questions are addressed in two complementary stages and the first is theoretical. It clarifies what unity amongst the citizens of a polity is, why it is important, how it differs from similar ideas and the ethical and unethical ways in which it can be fostered. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The second stage is empirical. New archival documents and numerous interviews with politicians and civil servants are used to understand how the governments of two parliamentary democracies, Britain and Canada, have actually attempted to foster such unity. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>Spanning political theory and political science, the project has strong application to Britain, and is a timely study on a politically significant issue that is under-researched.&lt;/p>

